#Add sentiment score
# Add Sentiment Analysis columns
sia = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

# create a new column in the DataFrame to store the sentiment scores
data_sen = data.copy()
data_sen['sentiment_scores'] = data_sen['sentence_str'].apply(lambda x: sia.polarity_scores(x))

# extract the values from the sentiment_scores dictionary and assign them to new columns
# compound score ranges from -1 (neg) through 0 (neu) to 1 (pos)
data_sen['neg'] = data_sen['sentiment_scores'].apply(lambda x: x['neg'])
data_sen['neu'] = data_sen['sentiment_scores'].apply(lambda x: x['neu'])
data_sen['pos'] = data_sen['sentiment_scores'].apply(lambda x: x['pos'])
data_sen['compound_sent_score'] = data_sen['sentiment_scores'].apply(lambda x: x['compound'])

# Drop columns we are not going to use (all sentiment columns except of compund)
data_sen.drop(columns=['sentence_spacy','corpus_edition_date','sentiment_scores','pos','neg','neu'], inplace=True)

t1 = time.time()
for sc in schools:
    
    df_temp = data[data.school==sc]
    
    print('School = ', sc.upper(), ':')
    
    # render wordcloud
    mask = np.array(Image.open(f"{sc}.png"))
    text = " ".join(txt for txt in df_temp.sentence_lowered)
    wordcloud = WordCloud(stopwords=stopwords, max_font_size=50, max_words=500,
                          width = 600, height = 400,
                          background_color="white",mask = mask).generate(text)
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
    plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation="bilinear")
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(f"{sc}_cloud.png")
t2 = time.time()
print('Elapsed time: ', np.round(t2-t1,2))

Part 2: Data Story¶

An analysis on Stoicism¶

According to the definition on Google, Stoicism is defined as the endurance of pain or hardship without the display of feelings and without complaint. This sounds really cold,right? Like pains, hardship, and endurance. From my perspective, however, it is better to say it is a philosophy of life that maximizes positive emotions, reduces negative emotions and helps individuals to hone their virtues of character.

I want to dig deeper on Stoicism because this is the one I mostly agree with at my current stage by my personal understanding. Below I will share two my favorite sentences of this philosophy with my own interpretation, then, I will use some methodologies like word-to-vec and graphics to prove or disprove myself. At the same time, definitely we can had a better understanding of this minor philosophy and widen our view of the world!

# a function for testing w2v pairs
def test_w2v(model, pairs):
  for (pos, neg) in pairs:
    math_result = model.most_similar(positive=pos, negative=neg)
    print(f'Positive - {pos}\tNegative - {neg}')
    [print(f"- {result[0]} ({round(result[1],5)})") for result in math_result[:5]]
    print()

2.1 First Sentence¶

"Some things are in our control and others not. Things in our control are opinion, pursuit, desire, aversion, and, in a word, whatever are our own actions. Things not in our control are body, property, reputation, command, and, in one word, whatever are not our own actions. #enchiridion 1".

I really appreciate this sentence because it provides a better explanation of my doctrine, which is from the Serenity Prayer by Niebuhr:

"God, Grant me the SERENITY, to accept the things I cannot change, COURAGE to change the things I can, and the WISDOM to know the difference.".

I highly believe the unsatisfaction of anything is due to our unreal higher estimation. Face the truth and reality, accept the limit and weakness is the best way to live with myself from my perspective. But sometimes, it is hard to distinguish between those two things, fortunately, Stoicism provides us a baseline.

I'd like to check the explanations of "control", “opinion”, and "command" to testify my understanding and more details will be presented in the following blocks.

2.2 Second Sentence¶

"Remember, that not he who gives ill language or a blow insults, but the principle which represents these things as insulting. When, therefore, anyone provokes you, be assured that it is your own opinion which provokes you. #enchiridion 20".

I listed this sentence because I think it is the essence of freedom in spirit. Sometimes, we feel painful by blames because we are afraid of accepting the reality, or refuse to. We want to hide it. Reality cannot be hidden, it is always there. No one can hurt us is not a nonsense. With a strong heart, accurate understanding of myself, we are able to open to all ideas because we know most of them are untrue. Others cannot feel the exactly same way as us, so open to opinions but evaluate them by ourselves.

Words like "insult", "provoke", and "ill" are my targets. I am expecting to see those as subjective words and take a look at the timeline of related sentences to see whether there are changes of this opinion.

from collections import Counter
highlight125 = []
highlight170 = []
for words in df125['tokenized_txt']:
    for word in words:
        highlight125.append(word)

for words in df170['tokenized_txt']:
    for word in words:
        highlight170.append(word)
        
highlight125_clean = []
for word in highlight125:
    if word not in stopwords:
        highlight125_clean.append(word)
        
highlight170_clean = []
for word in highlight170:
    if word not in stopwords:
        highlight170_clean.append(word)

On the big picture, we cannnot say there is a big difference between sentences in 125 and 170, but notice that some words are missing. Power is the fifth frequent word in 125, but totally disappeard in 170, so as must and desire. From my perspective, it is more reasonable and closer to my current view. Some thing we cannot change, so "must" and "power" , this type of words, is inaccurate to describe something or some bahaviors.¶
